image.altText: A portrait photo of Nicole Zuritta.

props.synopsis: Nicole Zuritta's friend was murdered in one of Australia's most notorious serial killings, turning her world upside down. Almost three decades on, she wants to reframe the way victims of the Snowtown murders are remembered.

title.children: Nicole's housemate was a victim of the Snowtown killings. It turned her world upside down

image.altText: A women in a pink suits, sits on a pink armchair, holding three dogs.

props.synopsis: For decades, women in Australia have been told they should have more children for the good of the country, but  there's many reasons why more are choosing to stay child free.

title.children: Why it will take more than money to make Australian women have kids 'for the country'

image.altText: A side profile close up of Peter Dutton.

props.synopsis: The significance of a major political leader playing so divisive a card on our community is a step that shouldn't go unnoticed, no matter how inured to it we have become over the years in the wake of Pauline Hanson and "boat people" politics.

title.children: Dutton has reduced a massively complex issue to a populist and misleading piece of political mischief

image.altText: Kiwi crossing in New Zealand

props.synopsis: As New Zealanders grapple with high interest rates, stubborn inflation and general economic downturn, job losses have begun and more Kiwis than ever are leaving for good.

title.children: Every month, Australia gains 2,000 Kiwis as New Zealand's economy sheds jobs

image.altText: a composite image of a man going into the water at a perth and fog blankets sydney harbour

props.synopsis: For the second time this May, Australia's normally mobile weather systems have ground to a halt, with the coming week bringing another prolonged spell of invariable day-to-day weather.

title.children: Australia's weather map freezes for second time, laying the platform for record May in Perth, Adelaide and parts of NSW

image.altText: Les Cameron stands out the front of his pub.

props.synopsis: Inspired by the legacy of Ernest Hemingway's free room and board in Paris, a footballer turned publican is offering a comfy bed and warm meal for anyone pursuing an artistic endeavour.

title.children: Les will let you stay in his old-fashioned country pub for free. He just asks for one thing in return

image.altText: Golfer Scottie Scheffler in an orange jumpsuit in his mugshot.

props.synopsis: World number one Scottie Scheffler is detained by police just hours before the second round of the PGA Championship after trying to drive past a traffic incident.

title.children: World number one golfer arrested outside PGA Championship just before second round

image.altText: a man holding a mug in the kitchen

props.synopsis: After decades as a big coffee drinker, Jesse recently gave it away, and says he is already noticing health improvements. Experts agree there is a range of benefits to ditching the daily grind.

title.children: Life after coffee: Why quitting caffeine makes sense for your mind and your bank balance

image.altText: A composite image of two men and one woman

props.synopsis: If the Coalition wants to topple the Albanese government next year, they need to gain ground in both WA and QLD. Here's what voters in those battleground seats care about.

title.children: 'Better than a kick in the pants': What everyday Australians think about Albanese's budget

image.altText: A map of Australia with a fingerprint on a background of $100 bills

props.synopsis: If budgets are the government's attempt to chart the course for the next few years, what can this one teach us about how climate change is leaving its mark, and how the government is looking to tackle it?

title.children: Thinking a greener future is costly? The fingerprints of climate change are already all over this budget

image.altText: Australian Prime Minister Anthony Albanese attends a rally to a call for action to end violence against women.

props.synopsis: Spending on domestic violence prevention in this year's budget was dwarfed by funds apportioned for fighting terrorism. Yet in the last three decades more than 1,500 women have been killed by intimate partners in Australia, compared with nine people killed in acts of terrorism. Is it time to change our approach?

title.children: Should we treat domestic violence like we treat terrorism?

image.altText: Nine soldiers stand inside in uniform wearing helmets, while others carry riot shields looking away from the camera

props.synopsis: One thousand additional security personnel have been deployed across New Caledonia to bring riots that have gripped the island to a halt.

title.children: Violence eases in New Caledonia as concerns grow about access to food and medicine

image.altText: Very young smooth-looking platypus babies held in a pair of hands at night close-up.

props.synopsis: Kangaroos have joeys and dingoes have pups, but what do you call a baby platypus? If you think "puggle", think again.

title.children: What is a baby platypus called: platypup, puggle, nestling or something else?

image.altText: smoke over buildings.

props.synopsis: Experts and observers say the discord in New Caledonia has built amid a deepening economic divide and a prolonged stalemate over the future of its status as a French territory.

title.children: New Caledonia's unrest has unfolded rapidly, but some say the strife was years in the making

image.altText: A split image of a woman hanging from an obstacle course, a man wielding swords, a woman holding a bow and arrow with her feet

image.altText: A female piano teacher conducts a lesson for a female student inside a classroom

image.altText: Snowtown accomplice Mark Haydon in a cap and jumper.

image.altText: city buildings

image.altText: Rows of solar panels in front of some wind turbines.

image.altText: Two young boys in white T-shirts stand in the foreground underneath an Israeli flag as smoke rises from a town in the distance.

image.altText: Business people walk outside the Reserve Bank of Australia.

image.altText: A mum sits with her two kids in school uniform

image.altText: A composite image of an older man and an older woman smiling.

image.altText: A zoomed-in view down an alleyway shows four men standing in front of a building marked with blue and yellow Stars of David.

image.altText: A person removing tattoos from a man's arm, both wearing protective glasses and sitting

image.altText: Man in hospital receiving care

image.altText: Overturned rail cars with iron ore in them.

image.altText: Vandals cut down 135-year-old statue of former Tasmanian premier William Crowther

image.altText: Split image of colourful lights in the sky and a singer standing on a platform with arms open
